   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2735_1.jpg"/>

            <note rend="pencil" hand="#ps:TH"><hi rend="underline">Edmund Gosse</hi>.</note>

            <opener>
               <address rend="letterhead">
                  <addrLine>17, Hanover Terrace,</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Regent's Park, N.W.</addrLine>
               </address>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1906-07-23">23.7.06</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>My dear Hardy</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>After long want of success, I have been fortunate enough to get (at a
                     <subst><del>price</del><add place="above">cost</add></subst> much exceeding,
               indeed, the original price!) a very fair copy of the first edition of "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1874_FarFromTheMaddingCrowd">Far from the Madding Crowd</ref>",
               in the green and gilt boards. I am extremely pleased, for this book has peculiar and
               even sentimental interest for me.</p>

            <p>Now I want you to be so very kind as to tell <pb n="2" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2735_2.jpg"/>
               me how the illustrations came to be made. Some are signed "<persName
                  ref="#ps:HelenAllingham">H. Paterson</persName>" others "<persName
                  ref="#ps:HelenAllingham"> H. Allingham</persName>". Was the lady married while the
               book was appearing? Did you know her and direct her pencil?</p>

            <p>Anything you can re­member about the history of these pictures will be very welcome
               if you will indulge me with it, and will forgive the curiosity of a tiresome old
               bibliomaniac.</p>

            <p>I hope you and <pb n="3" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2735_3.jpg"/>
               <persName ref="#ps:EmmaHardy"><abbr>M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi></abbr>
                  Hardy</persName> are neither of you any the worse for your <placeName
                  ref="#pl:London"> London</placeName> visit? My poor <persName ref="#ps:EllenGosse"
                  >Nellie</persName> is still confined to the room in which you saw her.</p>

            <p>I am going at the end of the week to stay at <placeName ref="#pl:Rye">Rye</placeName>
               with <persName ref="#ps:HenryJames">Henry James</persName>.</p>

            <closer>
               <salute>Always yours</salute>
               <signed>Edmund Gosse</signed>
            </closer>

            <postscript>
               <p>P.S. Have you had any con­firmation of that curious story about <persName
                     ref="#ps:MarieMeredith">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> R—l St—rg—s</persName>?
                  I have been discretion itself.</p>
            </postscript>

            <pb n="4" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2735_4.jpg"/>


         </div>

